[Annotator "IM Luis Rodi"]
[PlyCount "22"]
[EventDate "2019.??.??"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {After this move, planning the fianchetto
of the light-squared bishop, we have reached the starting position of the
Catalan Opening. This opening is not only considered to be a very solid choice
by White, but, thanks to rather recent developments from this century, also
full of dynamic and original ideas. According to my database, the first game
with this position is Prokes - Wagner, London ol 1927. Among the first
defenders of this idea we can find masters like Vladimir Alatorzev, Karel
Opocensky, Salo Flohr and Reuben Fine. The name of the opening originates from
the Barcelona tournament of 1929, when a special prize was given to the player
who introduced a new opening, which then would be named the Catalan. The
combination of Queens Gambit and hypermodern fianchetto opening won the votes
of the jury, and the prize went to Savielly Tartakower. Since these times,
many great players contributed to the development of his system, for instance,
in the seventies and eighties of the previous century, Oleg Romanishin created
highly dynamic ways to play for White, involving many interesting pawn
sacrifices. Later Vladimir Kramnik played the Catalan very successfully and
introduced new and important ideas for both sides. Today, most elite players
have the Catalan in their repertoire. But it's not just the elite, the opening
also had a huge surge in popularity among amateurs thanks to two excellent
books written by Boris Avrukh and Viktor Bologan.} Bb4+ {This check, played
first in Broder - Tartakower, Ljubljana 1938, is very useful. Black's goal is
to disturb the coordination of White's pieces on the queenside. The move is a
frequent choice of top players like Magnus Carlsen, Fabiano Caruana and many
more.} 5. Bd2 {The main reply, as the alternatives allow Black to capture on
c4 under favourable circumstances:} (5. Nc3 {This is a mix between the Catalan,
the Nimzo with g3 and the Ragozin. In my view, the principled reply here is}
dxc4 {, although 5...0-0 is more popular. This position is analysed in CHAPTER
1. Our main line is} 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O Nc6 8. Bg5 ({In my view, the move} 8. a3
{is undeservedly popular, as it weakens the b3 square.}) 8... h6 9. Bxf6 Qxf6
10. e3 Rb8 {, with very rich play ahead.}) ({On} 5. Nbd2 {can be answered the
same with} dxc4 {, which is analysed in CHAPTER 2. Black also has a good
alternative in playing Bogo-Indian style with 5...0-0, which is in fact the
choice of top grandmasters like Magnus Carlsen, Sergey Karjakin or Liam Le
Quang. This can lead to independent lines like 6.Bg2 b5 7.0-0 a5.}) 5... Be7 {
Of course, we don't give the check to exchange bishops. But while the Black
retreat to e7 was early virtually mandatory, in the last years, the
alternative 5...Bd6, first played in 1985 by Tamas Utasi, also won its share
of supporters. For instance, it's Richard Pert's choice in his repertoire book
on the QG Ragozin.} 6. Bg2 {Almost a universal move here. In CHAPTER 3 we will
see some other options for White on move 6 and 7.} O-O 7. O-O {Again the most
natural. While other moves usually transposes, a few independent options are
possible - see CHAPTER 3.} Nbd7 {This is my suggested move-order.} (7... c6 {
usually transposes, but some independent ways are available for both players,
most importantly} 8. Qc2 Nbd7 9. Rd1 Ne4 10. Be1 $5 {, where White keeps his
dark-squared bishop far away from any further harassment. This and other ideas
are also explored in CHAPTER 3.}) 8. Qc2 {The main continuation, but not the
only one by far. There are almost unexplored ways supported by well-known
players: Levon Aronian's 8.Na3, Wesley So's 8.b4, Boris Gelfand's 8.c5... I
will introduce them and other less popular options in CHAPTER 4.} (8. Qb3 {
deserves its own space, as it is the second most popular idea in this position.
American prodigy Hikaru Nakamura as well as classic players like Ulf Andersson
and Ljubomir Ljobojevic played this way, avoiding the theoretical main lines.
Black has at least two good replies in 8...Nb6 and 8...c6. CHAPTER 5 is
dedicated to this line.}) 8... Ne4 {This dynamic approach is our repertoire
choice.} ({The main move here is} 8... c6 9. Bf4 b6 {(note that 8...Ne4
transposes to our line), a solid and trustworthy alternative, but out of our
scope. Meanwhile, I recommend it to readers as a practical option if our main
line needs a pit-stop for repair.}) 9. Bf4 {Very logical, keeping the bishop's
pair.} ({The main alternative is} 9. Nc3 {, allowing the exchange on d2, when
after} Nxd2 10. Nxd2 {White tries to gain central influence by the e4 advance
as compensation for the loss of his bishop pair. CHAPTER 6 analyses this and
other less common ideas for White on the 9th move, including the popular 9.Rd1.
}) 9... c6 {This is the basic position from our development scheme. We can
arrive here using various move-orders, although each of them presents a series
of independent sublines.} 10. Nc3 {This active development move is the most
popular in this position. White also played} (10. Nbd2 {This simple way of
developing does not cause Black any troubles, who can immediately grab the
initiative with 10...g5! 11.Be3 Nd6. Along with other less popular ideas, this
line is analysed in CHAPTER 7.}) (10. Nfd2 {is an idea recommended by
grandmaster Boris Avrukh in his excellent repertoire series with 1.d4. I think
that Black has equal play with the reply} g5 $5 {, and if 11.Be3, the
manoeuvre 11...Nd6 with the idea ...Nf5 works well - see CHAPTER 8 for details.
}) 10... g5 {An energetic move and Mikhail Botvinnik's idea. The great
champion chose it in his match against Tigran Petrosian (1963, ninth game).
This background and the extraordinary game Eljanov - Carlsen, Wijk aan Zee
2016, inspired me to include the line in my repertoire.} 11. Bc1 {Petrosian's
choice, and the most popular in a ratio of 2:1. The alternative is} (11. Be3 {
that was the move chosen by Eljanov in the abovementioned game. Along with a
less usual 11.Bd2, this possibility is analysed in CHAPTER 9, where the
manoeuvre 11...Nd6 12.b3 Nf5 is recommended.}) 11... f5 {After this advance,
Black gets an active position in Stonewall style. At first glance, the
difference from the original Dutch opening seems to be in Black's favour, who
is a few tempi ahead. This gives him a strong grip on e4 and the positional
basis for a quick expansion on the kingside. Meanwhile, White also has his
standard ideas: His control of the e5 square, the presence of a bad bishop in
Black's camp, and he can hope to exploit the weaknesses created by the advance
of the black kingside pawns. To summarize, it's a complex and strategically
rich position with chances for both sides. We will explore it further in
CHAPTER 10. But that is not all. White can apply move-orders that make it
difficult to obtain the abovementioned schemes. CHAPTER 11 deals with these
move-order deviations. One of them is 1.d4 d5 2.c4 e6 3.g3, where 3... Nf6 4.
Bg2 Bb4+ 5.Nd2 (or 5.Nc3) does not allow ...dxc4 because of Qa4+. But after 5..
.0-0, White hardly has anything better than 6.Nf3, transposing to chapters 1
or 2. Another possible deviation is 1.d4 d5 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.g3 Nf6 4. Bg2,
delaying c4. This way White prevents the bishop check and, of course, any
pawn-grabbing ideas on c4, but Black has the interesting reply 4...b5. Now the
main continuation is 5.0-0 Bb7 6.a4 b4, when after 7.c4 c5 8.Nbd2 I will
analyse the unpublished 8...Be7. This and some secondary lines are presented
in the final CHAPTER 12.} *

