1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Nc3 {This position is usually
reached from the Nimzoindian with g3 or, to a lesser degree, from the Queens
Gambit Ragozin. In the Catalan, White usually develops his queen's knight to
a3 or d2 after Black captures on c4, which explains the next move.} dxc4 {
While simple development with 5...0-0 is possible and, in fact, the most
frequently played continuation, I prefer this capture, which is also
recommended in Richard Pert's and Matthieu Cornette's books on the Ragozin.} 6.
Bg2 {The main continuation.} ({White also tried} 6. Qa4+ {, but Black has a
good position after} Nc6 7. a3 (7. Bg2 Nd5 $15) 7... Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 Qd5 9. Bg2
Bd7 10. Qc2 (10. Nh4 Na5 $17) 10... Na5 $15 {Leutwyler - Wirthensohn, 2002})
6... O-O (6... Nc6 {is Pert's move-order, which transposes to the text after}
7. O-O O-O) 7. O-O Nc6 8. Bg5 {Recently this has proven to be the most
reliable line for White. The alternatives, by order of popularity, are:} ({a)} 
8. a3 {This is the most popular try, immediately asking the advanced bishop
about his intentions.} Be7 {Keeping the bishop. A problem with the previous
White move is the weakened the b3-square, which Black can occupy.} 9. e4 {
The main line. Alternatives don't cause Black any difficulties.} (9. e3 {
, after which Black even better:} Na5 10. Qe2 (10. Nd2 c6 11. Qe2 {[Pajeken -
Dragun, Wroclaw rapid 2014]} b6 $1 $17) (10. Ne5 Nd7 11. f4 c5 $17 {Zierke -
Kacheishvili, Berlin 1995}) 10... Rb8 (10... Bd7 $5 $13 {Perelshtein -
Sargissian, Chicago 2009}) 11. a4 Nd5 (11... b6 $5 $13 {, as in Adhiban -
Bocharov, Bhubaneswar 2010 deserves consideration.}) 12. Bd2 c6 (12... b6 13.
Ne5 Bb7 $15 {Cornette}) 13. Ne5 Nb3 14. Rad1 f6 15. Nxc4 b5 $15) 9... Na5 {
Black's main choice.} ({Both Cornette and Pert mention the option} 9... a6 $5 {
without delving into concrete lines. The English master points that "Black
maintains pressure on the d4-pawn in the short term before switching the
knight to a5." I believe the reason lies in the 10.Bf4 set-up, when it is
useful for Black to keep the option of ...c6 and ...b5, so that he will not
have to worry about the defence of the c7 pawn. A recent example is} 10. Bf4 b5
11. Qe2 Bb7 12. Rad1 Na5 13. Ne5 Nb3 14. d5 exd5 15. exd5 Bd6 $15 {Flom -
Beliavsky, Skopje 2019}) 10. Be3 {Now Black has several options:} (10. Qe2 Nb3
(10... c6 {is one of Pert's solutions:} 11. Bf4 b5 12. Rad1 Bb7 13. Ne5 $5 a6
14. g4 Nb3 $132 {Battaglini - Svetushkin, 2011}) 11. e5 Nd5 (11... Nxa1 12.
exf6 Bxf6 13. Qxc4 $44 {Battaglini - Soffer, Israel 2012}) 12. Rb1 Nxc3 (12...
a5 13. Qxc4 a4 14. Rd1 Bd7 15. Nd2 {[Sandipan - Vera, Cappelle 2010]} Na5 16.
Qd3 Bc6 $13 {Pert}) 13. bxc3 Nxc1 14. Rfxc1 c5 (14... Bxa3 15. Rd1 {is perhaps
less clear, even with the two extra pawns for Black}) 15. Qxc4 Rb8 16. Rd1 (16.
dxc5 Qc7 17. c6 {[Battaglini - Favarel, Nimes 2014]} Bd7 $5 18. a4 bxc6 $13 {
Cornette}) 16... Qc7 $11 {Sandipan - Gajewski, Cappelle la Grande 2010}) (10.
Bf4 Nb3 ({Pert prefers} 10... c6 {, where} 11. Qe2 b5 12. Rad1 Bb7 {transposes
to 10.Qe2, but also considers the text as safe and reliable.}) 11. Rb1 c6 $5 (
11... c5 12. dxc5 {[Li Shilong - Hou Yifan, China tt 2011]} Nd7 13. Qe2 Ndxc5
14. Rfd1 Qe8 15. Qxc4 b6 $11 {Cornette}) 12. Ne5 $5 Qxd4 13. Qxd4 Nxd4 14. Rfd1
Nb3 15. Nxc4 Rd8 $5 ({or Pert's} 15... b6) 16. Rxd8+ Bxd8 17. Rd1 Be7 $15) ({
Nobody plays} 10. e5 {, and for a good reason: White doesn't have anything for
the pawn after} Nd5 11. Ne4 Nb3 12. Rb1 b5 $17) 10... a6 $5 {Now White has a
number of options:} (10... Nb3 {is Cornette's recommendation. After} 11. Rb1 c5
(11... Qe8 $5) 12. dxc5 (12. d5 exd5 13. exd5 Bf5 $17) 12... Bxc5 13. Qe2 (13.
Qxd8 Rxd8 14. Ne5 b6 15. Nc6 Rd7 16. Ne5 {, and a draw was declared in Kuemin
- Ravi, Biel 2000, but Black can continue with} Bxe3 17. Nxd7 Nxd7 18. fxe3 Nd2
$17) (13. Bxc5 Nxc5 14. Qxd8 Rxd8 15. Ne5 b6 16. Nc6 Re8 17. e5 Nd5 18. Nxd5
exd5 19. Bxd5 Bb7 20. f4 Rad8 21. Bh1 Rd7 $11 {Nguyen Huynh Minh - Hossain, Al
Ain 2015}) 13... Bxe3 14. Qxe3 {(Sambuev - Lesiege, Quebec 2018)} Qe8 $5 15.
Rbd1 e5 $13 {the game is roughly balanced.}) (10... Rb8 11. Qe2 b5 {is another
solution suggested by Pert.} 12. Rad1 a6 13. d5 Qe8 14. Rfe1 Nb3 {(Onischuk -
Karjakin,. Baku 2015)} 15. Nd4 Nxd4 16. Bxd4 Bb7 17. Bxf6 (17. f4 exd5 18. e5
Ne4 19. Nxe4 dxe4 20. Bxe4 Bxe4 21. Qxe4 $44) 17... Bxf6 18. e5 Be7 $11 {Pert})
(10... c6 $5 11. Qe2 (11. Qc2 b5 12. Rad1 Bb7 13. Ne5 Qc7 14. f4 Rad8 15. g4 a6
16. g5 Ne8 $13 {Salem - Movsisian, internet 2019}) 11... b5 12. Rad1 Bb7 13.
Ne5 Qc7 14. Bf4 (14. f4 Nb3 15. g4 Rad8 16. g5 Nd7 $13) 14... Qb6 $13 {
Urtnasan - Nguyen Van Huy, Ulaanbaatar 2019}) 11. Qc2 {Pert prefers this move.}
(11. Qe2 b5 12. Rad1 Bb7 {, and now} 13. Ne5 (13. Bf4 {can be answered with 13.
..Nb3 or} Nh5 $5 14. Be5 f6 15. Ng5 fxg5 16. Qxh5 Nc6 17. Qg4 Qd7 $15 {Li Chao
- Tkachiev, Jakarta 2011}) 13... Qe8 14. f4 (14. Bg5 Rd8 15. Ng4 Nxg4 16. Qxg4
Bxg5 17. Qxg5 Nb3 $17 {Kanter - Beliavsky, Yerevan 2014}) 14... Rd8 {is a bit
better for the second player, for instance:} 15. g4 Nb3 16. g5 Nd7 17. h4 Nxe5
18. fxe5 Kh8 19. Bh3 {Here Pert gives 19...Bc8 or 19...c6, with a slight
advantage for Black.} a5 $5 $15 {also comes into consideration.}) 11... b5 12.
Rad1 (12. Ng5 {(Feldborg-Rasmussen, corr 2006)} Ng4 $5 13. e5 Bxg5 14. Bxg5
Qxg5 15. Bxa8 c6 $15) 12... Bb7 $5 {One more time, Black has several decent
alternatives. For example, the next two are tested in practice:} ({a)} 12...
Nd7 13. h4 c5 14. e5 cxd4 15. Rxd4 $44 {Delorme - Campos Moreno, Chambery 2014}
) ({b)} 12... c6 {Pert recommends this move in his book, giving the
continuation} 13. d5 $5 exd5 14. exd5 Nxd5 15. Nxd5 cxd5 16. Ng5 Bxg5 17. Rxd5
Qc7 18. Rc5 Qe7 19. Rxg5 Bb7 20. Rh5 {(Akshat - Debashis, Kolkata 2014). Now
the English master suggests} f5 $5 21. Bxb7 Nxb7 22. Rxf5 Rxf5 23. Qxf5 Rd8 24.
h4 Qf7 $13) 13. d5 Qe8 $1 {A very strong reply. The queen steps away from the
rook's influence and can even be transfered to the kingside in some lines.} 14.
Bh3 $5 (14. Bf4 Bd8 15. a4 (15. Rfe1) (15. Nd2 e5 16. Be3 Bc8 $15) 15... b4 16.
Nb1 exd5 17. exd5 Bxd5 18. Nbd2 Qc6 19. Ne5 Qe6 20. Nexc4 Bxg2 21. Kxg2 Qc6+
22. Kg1 Re8 $15) 14... Nb3 $1 (14... exd5 15. e5 d4 16. Nxd4 Nd7 17. f4 $44)
15. dxe6 fxe6 (15... Bd6 16. exf7+ Rxf7 17. Rfe1 Nxe4 18. Bg2 $44) 16. Bxe6+
Kh8 {White balances the material, but his pieces lack coordination.} 17. Bf5
Qh5 $15) ({b)} 8. Re1 Rb8 9. e4 b5 {Black scored good results in this line, as
White has difficulties justifying his material deficit.} 10. a3 $5 (10. e5 Nd5
11. Ng5 h6 12. Nge4 Be7 $15 {Gormally - Kosten, Torquay 2013}) 10... Ba5 $5 {
The critical retreat} (10... Be7 11. Bf4 a6 $5 {Sunye Neto - Toth, Porto Velho
1988} ({or} 11... Na5 {Vera - Norris, Mexico 1980. In both cases White has
decent compensation.})) 11. Bg5 h6 12. Bh4 e5 $1 (12... Ne7 13. Bxf6 gxf6 $13 {
Bukal - Palac, Schwarzach 2012}) (12... g5 13. Nxg5 hxg5 14. Bxg5 Qxd4 15. Qxd4
Nxd4 16. Bxf6 Bxc3 17. bxc3 Nc2 18. e5 Nxe1 19. Rxe1 Bb7 20. Bxb7 Rxb7 21. Re4
$13) 13. d5 (13. Nxe5 Nxe5 14. dxe5 Qxd1 15. Rexd1 Nd7 16. f4 Nxe5 17. fxe5 g5
$17) 13... Bxc3 14. bxc3 Na5 $17 {I cannot see any compensation here.}) ({c)} 
8. Qa4 Nd5 9. Qc2 {is an interesting idea played, among others, by Anatoly
Karpov and Fabiano Caruana. It's also the recommendation of GM Jose Gonzalez
in his work for Modern Chess on the Nimzo-Indian Romanishin Variation for
White. The idea is to distract the king's knight from the defence of the black
king.} Be7 $1 {Leaving the b4 square for the knights.} 10. Rd1 {My
recommendation here is} Ncb4 $5 (10... Rb8 11. e4 Ndb4 12. Qe2 Nd3 (12... Na5
$5) 13. Be3 b5 14. b3 Ba6 15. d5 exd5 16. Nxd5 Bd6 17. Ne1 Nxe1 18. Qxe1 Ne5
19. Bxa7 Ra8 20. Bd4 {is Gonzalez main line, giving White a slight advantage.})
(10... f5 $5 11. b3 {This is not critical} ({Perhaps} 11. e4 $5) ({or} 11. a3
$5) 11... Ncb4 12. Qb2 cxb3 13. Qxb3 Nxc3 14. Qxc3 Nd5 15. Qb3 b6 $132 {
Stocek - Anton Guijarro, Prague 2019}) 11. Qd2 {The most popular, and the only
move played in the last months.} ({Gonzalez recommends the alternative} 11. Qb1
Nxc3 12. bxc3 Nd5 13. Qc2 {where besides Gonzalez's 13...Bd7 Black can consider
} Nb6 14. Re1 ({, but not the premature} 14. e4 $6 Bd7 $15) 14... c5 $13 {
with chances for both sides.}) 11... Nb6 (11... c5 $5 12. a3 (12. dxc5 Nxc3 13.
bxc3 Nd5 14. Qc2 Qc7 $132 {Jones - Koneru, Gibralar 2019}) 12... Nc6 13. Qc2
cxd4 14. Nxd4 {[Landa - Mons, Germany 2019]} Qa5 $13) 12. a3 N4d5 13. e4 Nxc3
14. Qxc3 Bd7 $13 {Harsha - Iturrizaga, Dubai 2019. While White has a good
centre, the black position is solid and the pawn counts for something. Chances
are roughly equal.}) ({d)} 8. e3 Rb8 9. Qe2 (9. Nd2 e5 $15 {Zhao Xue - Xu
Yuanyuan, China 2005}) 9... b5 10. Rd1 Nd5 $5 (10... Qe7 {is Cornette's choice.
} 11. e4 e5 12. dxe5 Nxe5 13. Nxe5 Qxe5 14. Bf4 Qe7 15. a4 a6 16. axb5 axb5 17.
h3 Be6 $13 {Akshayraj - Moradiabadi, New York 2014}) ({while} 10... Be7 {
is Pert's suggestion, but he doesn't consider} 11. Ne5 $5 {, after which} Na5
12. Bd2 $44 {offers decent play for White.}) 11. Bd2 Bd6 12. e4 $5 (12. Ne1
Nxc3 13. bxc3 Bb7 {Zeng C. - Wen Yang, China 2018}) (12. a3 a6 13. e4 {[Bedos
- Scholz, France 1989]} Nb6 $15) 12... Nxc3 13. bxc3 Na5 14. Nh4 $5 a6 15. Be3
Bb7 $15) ({e)} 8. Bf4 Nd5 (8... Rb8 $5 {Feofanov - Baginskaite, Vilna 2019}) 9.
Bd2 (9. Rc1 Rb8 10. Ne4 b5 11. Bd2 Be7 $15 {Bach - Tischbierek, Berlin 1992})
9... a6 $15) ({f)} 8. Rb1 Rb8 9. a3 Be7 10. Qa4 Nxd4 (10... a6 $5 11. Qxc4 b5
12. Qd3 b4 13. axb4 Nxb4 14. Qc4 Bb7 $11 {Enkhnar - Biriukov, 2016}) 11. Nxd4
Qxd4 12. Be3 Qe5 13. Qxa7 Bd7 14. Rfd1 {(Sandipan - Gustafsson, Sarajevo 2010).
Now I like Cornette's} Qf5 $5 15. Bxb7 c6 $13) 8... h6 {I remember the
Argentinean master Roberto Grau explain in one of his books that this advance
is stronger in fianchetto positions, because in most cases the bishop cannot
retreat to the edge of the board.} (8... Rb8 $5 {is another try.} 9. a3 Be7 10.
Qa4 h6 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. e3 b5 13. Nxb5 Bd7 14. Nxa7 {was played in Gaehwiler
- Lagunow, Radenci 2019. Here Black has several interesting replies. My
preference is} Nxd4 15. Qxc4 Nb5 16. Nc6 Nd6 17. Qc5 Bxc6 18. Qxc6 Rb6 $44) 9.
Bxf6 (9. Bf4 {keeps the bishop pair, but now} Nd5 10. Bd2 {[Thapa - Zhao Zong,
Sidney 2016]} Rb8 {is better for Black}) 9... Qxf6 10. e3 {This solid set-up
is the most accurate, in my view.} ({White also can play} 10. Ne4 Qf5 11. Ned2
(11. Qc2 Rd8 {and, as Pert writes, it is not easy for White to recover the
pawn:} 12. Rfd1 Be7 13. e3 {[Safin - Bakre, Kolkata 2008]} b5 $17) 11... Bxd2
12. Qxd2 e5 13. Rad1 Nxd4 (13... e4 $5) 14. Nxd4 exd4 15. Qxd4 c6 16. Qxc4 Qe6
$11 {Baranowski - Risque, corr 2017.}) (10. e4 {looks very ambitious, but this
centre can be attacked with} Bxc3 (10... Rb8 $5 {is the computer's move}) 11.
bxc3 e5 12. d5 Na5 $15) 10... Rb8 {Planning ...b5.} (10... Rd8 {is Cornette's
recommendation, for example} 11. Nd2 e5 12. Nd5 Rxd5 13. Bxd5 Bh3 14. Nxc4 Bxf1
15. dxe5 Nxe5 16. Nxe5 Qxe5 17. Kxf1 Rf8 18. Qb3 c6 19. Bf3 Qe7 $11 {Tanti -
Johnson, corr 2011}) 11. Ne4 (11. Nd2 {is more popular, but Black is somewhat
better after} Na5 {, for instance:} 12. Qc2 ({or} 12. Qa4 Qe7 13. a3 Bxc3 14.
bxc3 b6 $15 {Jegorovas - Fischer, corr 2008}) 12... Qd8 13. a3 Be7 {[Schaefer
- Hjartarson, Porto Mannu 2015]} 14. Nce4 b5 $15) 11... Qf5 (11... Qg6 $5 {
is Pert's main continuation in his book.} 12. Ned2 ({The Englishman follows up
with} 12. Qc2 Be7 13. b3 $5 {, with some compensation for the pawn.}) 12... b5
13. a4 a6 14. axb5 axb5 15. Nh4 Qd3 16. Nxc4 bxc4 17. Bxc6 Rb6 18. Qa4 {
with balanced play in Oliveira - Dunlop, corr 2016}) (11... Qe7 12. a3 Bd6 13.
Nfd2 {, and now 13. ..Na5 [Sandipan - Khalifman, Moscow 2016] or} b5 {[Miton -
Balogh, Katowice 2010]. White has compensation, but no more than that.}) (11...
Qd8 $5 {was tested in some correspondence games. After} 12. Qc2 b5 13. b3 Na5
14. Ne5 {White has compensation, for instance:} Bb7 15. bxc4 Nxc4 16. Nxc4 bxc4
17. Qxc4 Bd5 18. Qa6 c5 19. dxc5 Qc8 $11 {Mahnke - Beck, corr 2015}) 12. a3 {
It's time to ask the advanced bishop about his intentions.} (12. Nfd2 b5 $15 {
Potapov - Yakovich, Salekhard 2007}) (12. Nh4 $5 Qa5 (12... Qh7 $5) 13. f4 Be7
$13) 12... Be7 13. Nfd2 Na5 $5 ({Or} 13... b5 14. a4 $44) 14. Qa4 b6 15. Nxc4
Nxc4 16. Qxc4 c5 {With roughly equal play. While White's appears to be
slightly more active, Black has the bishop pair. Captures on c5 will open the
b-file for his rook.} *

