1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Nbd2 {The other square for the
queen's knight. While it may look more solid than 5.Nc3, the knight is also
less active placed in case White needs to justify a pawn sacrifice.} dxc4 {
The capture exploits the current lack of coordination among the white pieces.
It is also Pert's recommendation in his book "Playing the Ragozin".} ({The
main alternative, with a strong resemblance to the Bogo-Indian, is} 5... O-O 6.
Bg2 b6 (6... dxc4 {is also possible, transposing to our line.}) 7. O-O Bb7 {
This has been played by top grandmasters like Magnus Carlsen, Fabiano Caruana
and Liang Le Quang.}) 6. Bg2 {It is important for White to exert pressure on
the long diagonal.} ({Less critical seems the alternative} 6. Qc2 {, when} b5
7. a4 c6 8. Bg2 Bb7 9. O-O O-O 10. b3 (10. Rd1 Nbd7 11. b3 c3 12. Nb1 Qa5 13.
Ne1 Nd5 14. Nd3 c5 15. e4 N5f6 16. dxc5 Nxc5 17. Nxb4 Qxb4 18. Nxc3 Nxb3 19.
Qb2 a5 $17 {Ernst - Illner, Amsterdam 2012}) 10... c5 (10... c3 {transposes to
the main line after 7...0-0.}) 11. bxc4 bxc4 12. Nxc4 ({White lacks
compensation after} 12. Bb2 Bxd2 13. Qxd2 cxd4 14. Bxd4 Nbd7 15. Rfc1 Bd5 $15 {
Korley - Gajewski, Reykjavik 2015}) 12... cxd4 13. Qb3 Na6 14. Bb2 Rb8 $5 {
offers Black the initiative.}) (6. Qa4+ $6 {doesn't lead to anything:} Nc6 7.
a3 Bxd2+ 8. Bxd2 Qd5 $17 {, as in Jongsma - Langeweg, The Hague 1968.}) 6... b5
{Black defends the pawn in advance with this move, which is the most popular
and also scores best.} ({The main alternative is Pert's recommendation} 6...
O-O {, which is very interesting and can transpose to the text. I think that
here the critical move is} 7. a3 (7. O-O b5 {leads to a position that will be
analysed in the notes to Black's 7th move in the main line.}) (7. Qc2 a5 8. O-O
b5 9. a4 c6 {transposes to main line}) 7... Bxd2+ 8. Bxd2 Nc6 9. e3 {This move
isn't considered by Pert} (9. Bc3 Nd5 {[Arjun - Panelo, Montcada 2013]} 10. Qa4
Nb6 11. Qc2 $44) 9... Rb8 (9... b5 $5 {Abasov - Karjakin, Douglas 2019}) 10.
Qc2 b5 11. b3 Bb7 (11... Rb6 12. bxc4 bxc4 13. O-O Ba6 14. Rfc1 $14 {
Yankelevich - Schlosser, Pardubice 2018}) (11... Qd7 $5) 12. bxc4 bxc4 13. O-O
Ba6 {(Sychevskyy - Wang Tianqi, Budapest 2018)} 14. Rfd1 $44) 7. O-O {The main
continuation. Other options are} ({a)} 7. a4 c6 (7... c3 $5 8. bxc3 Bxc3 9. Rb1
b4 10. Ne5 Nd5 {, as in Rotstein - Trella, Alemanha 2009, is my computer's
preference, but it's not very popular.}) 8. O-O (8. Qc2 {was Carlsen's choice
in 2007. After} Bb7 9. O-O O-O 10. b3 c3 11. Nb1 c5 12. Nxc3 bxa4 13. dxc5 axb3
14. Qxb3 a5 {the position offers chances for both sides, Landa - Movsesian,
Czech Republic 2015.}) 8... a5 {with transposition to the main line.}) ({b)} 7.
Ne5 Nd5 8. O-O O-O 9. Qc2 $5 (9. a4 c6 10. Qc2 (10. e4 {is Pert's continuation,
but after} Nb6 11. Ndf3 f6 {Black is better}) 10... Bb7 (10... f6 11. Nef3 Be7
12. e4 Nb4 13. Qc3 Nd7 14. b3 $44 {Zaitsev - Nikolaevsky, Kharkov 1967}) 11.
Ne4 f6 12. Nf3 {(Naumann - Beliavsky, Alemanha 2005)} Nd7 $15) 9... a5 (9... f6
10. Nef3 a5 11. b3 $44) 10. a3 Bd6 $13) 7... a5 {This seems to me the most
ambitious black move, winning space on the queenside and giving new ways of
development to the queenside pieces, even the rook.} (7... O-O 8. a4 c6 9. b3 (
9. Qc2 Bb7 10. b3 {transposes to 6.Qc2}) 9... c3 10. Nb1 Bb7 11. Qc2 {
transposes to a position from the move-order 7.a4 c6.}) (7... Bb7 8. Nxc4 $1
bxc4 9. Qa4+ Nc6 10. Ne5 Nd5 11. Nxc6 Qd7 12. Bxd5 exd5 13. Qxb4 {with a white
initiative, Miroshnichenko - Hofmann, Germany 2005.}) 8. a4 {This is the most
popular and logical continuation, but White also tried some other moves:} ({a)
} 8. a3 Be7 9. b3 (9. a4 c6 10. Ne5 Nd5 11. Ne4 O-O $17 {Fominyh - Alekseev,
Russia t 2004}) 9... cxb3 (9... c3 10. Nb1 Bb7 11. Nxc3 b4 12. axb4 axb4 13.
Rxa8 Bxa8 14. Na4 Nbd7 {[Bosiocic - Pikula, Bosnia 2018] seems more
comfortable for White}) 10. Qxb3 (10. Nxb3 {(Bao - Rosen, Adelaide 2018)} Bb7
11. Bg5 Nbd7 $15) 10... c6 ({or} 10... O-O $5 11. Qxb5 c5 12. dxc5 Ba6 $44 {
(Vidit - Shyam, India 2015), but Black's position seems to me more difficult
to play than in the main line.}) 11. Bb2 O-O 12. Ne5 Bb7 13. Rfc1 Qb6 $5 (13...
Nd5 14. Ne4 Nb6 15. Rab1 Na4 16. Ba1 Ra6 $13 {Bosiocic - Palac, 2018}) 14. Ne4
(14. a4 b4 15. Qc2 Rc8 16. Ne4 Nfd7 $13) (14. Qc2 Rc8 15. Ne4 Nfd7 16. Nd3 Na6
$13) 14... Nxe4 (14... Nfd7 $5 {as in the previous note is also possible.}) 15.
Bxe4 Bf6 16. Qf3 Qc7 17. Rab1 Rc8 $13 {The position offers chances for both
sides.}) ({b)} 8. b3 {Playing for compensation this way is a bit premature:}
cxb3 9. Qxb3 Bb7 10. Qd3 (10. a3 Bd5 11. Qd3 Bxd2 12. Nxd2 Bxg2 13. Kxg2 O-O
14. Bb2 Nbd7 15. Rac1 Qb8 $15 {Mikhalevski - Korchnoi, Beersheba 1993}) 10...
c6 11. a4 (11. a3 Bd6 12. Bb2 O-O $15) 11... O-O $15 {Wang Yiye - Bluebaum,
Qatar 2015}) 8... c6 9. Qc2 Bb7 {This is my choice between other moves of
similar value.} (9... O-O {is the most popular here. After} 10. b3 (10. Ne4
Nxe4 11. Qxe4 Ra6 $11 {Kozul - Lalic, Croatia 2004}) (10. Ne5 {as in Kanter -
Frolyanov, Kazan 2019, can be answered with} Nd5 $15) 10... cxb3 (10... c3 11.
Nb1 bxa4 12. bxa4 Bb7 {transposes to our main line.}) 11. Nxb3 bxa4 12. Rxa4 ({
This is better than} 12. Nc5 Nbd7 $15 {, where White's compensation isn't
sufficient, Javanbakht - Ghaem Maghami, Iran ch 2018.}) 12... Ba6 {(Raetsky -
A.Sokolov, Geneve 2011)} 13. Ba3 (13. Bg5 Bb5 $15) 13... Bb5 14. Bxb4 Bxa4 15.
Bxf8 Qxf8 16. Ne5 Bb5 17. Ra1 $44 {"The best White can hope for is to be equal
after winning back a pawn." Pert}) ({Black also has} 9... Nd5 $5 {to
experiment with in this position.}) 10. b3 c3 $1 {I think this is necessary. A
different scheme arises from} (10... cxb3 11. Nxb3 {, for instance:} Nbd7 12.
Ne1 Nd5 13. Nd3 Be7 {Papaioannou - Macieja, Greece tt 2009. This type of
position offers White good compensation.}) 11. Nb1 bxa4 12. bxa4 ({The
alternative} 12. Nxc3 axb3 13. Qxb3 {offer chances for both sides, i. e.} O-O {
[Khmelniker - Yemelin, Plovdiv 2010]} 14. Ba3 Qe7 $13) 12... c5 {As White will
win back the pawn, it's important to activate the bishop b7 in order to avoid
a passive position.} 13. Nxc3 O-O 14. dxc5 Nbd7 15. Rd1 (15. Bf4 Nxc5 16. Rfd1
Qc8 17. Nb5 Nce4 18. Qxc8 Raxc8 $11 {Pogonina - Demianjuk, Sitges 2018}) (15.
Nb5 Nxc5 16. Rd1 Qe7 17. Ne5 {(Mikhalevski - Roiz, Gibraltar 2011)} Bxg2 18.
Kxg2 Nce4 $11) 15... Qe7 16. Nb5 {Draw was declared in Yu Yangyi - Yilmaz,
Khanty Mansiysk 2017. A possible continuation is} Be4 17. Qb2 Nxc5 18. Be3 h6
$11 {with a balanced position. The symmetry of the pawn structure makes any
attempt for an advantage difficult.} *

[Event "5.Bd2 intro and the move-order 7...c6"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "5"]
[White "CHAPTER 3"]
[Black "Catalan 4...Bb4+"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "E01"]
[Annotator "IM Luis Rodi"]
[PlyCount "26"]
[EventDate "2018.12.08"]
[EventCountry "RUS"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 {The main continuation, with
more than 6.000 games in the database. While d2 isn't the best square for the
white dark-squared bishop, this move is more flexible than the ones from the
previous chapters, because it's more easy to redirect this piece later.} Be7 {
This reply is my preference, but Black has alternatives like} (5... Bd6 {
, which is Pert's recommendation in his book on the Ragozin.}) 6. Bg2 {This
natural move that is (almost) a universal choice here. Sometimes the first
player varies with moves like} ({a)} 6. Qc2 {This usually leads to
transpositions after} O-O 7. Bg2 Nbd7 8. O-O Ne4 {, which is examined in the
next chapters.}) ({b)} 6. Nc3 {is an independent line. Quite often c3 is not
the best square for the queen's knight in the Catalan, and this is also true
here.} O-O (6... dxc4 $5 {is also possible}) 7. Bg2 (7. cxd5 {appears among
the first options of the computer, and in the databases it is the second most
popular option, but in my view it lacks sense because it allows the
improvement of the black light-squared bishop.} exd5 8. Bg2 c6 9. O-O Bf5 10.
Nh4 Be6 {[Zaja - Rusck, Austria 2004]. Black doesn't have any problems here.}
11. f4 Re8 12. f5 Bc8 $15 {, and it's hard to find a constructive plan for
White.}) 7... dxc4 8. Qa4 (8. O-O {[Jacobsen - Azarov, Rijeka 2010]} Nc6 $5 9.
Bg5 Nd5 10. h4 f6 11. Bd2 Nb6 $15) 8... a6 9. Qxc4 b5 10. Qd3 Bb7 $36 {
Johansson - Sargissian, Copenhagen 2007. Black is ready for ...c5.}) 6... O-O
7. O-O {Again the most natural. Other 7th white moves usually transpose:} ({a)
} 7. Qc2 Nbd7 (7... b6 $5 8. O-O Bb7 {Quinteros - Larsen, Bled/Portoroz 1979
it a way to look for independent play.}) 8. O-O Ne4 {leads to our main line.})
({b)} 7. Nc3 dxc4 8. Qa4 a6 {transposes to the abovementioned 6.Nc3.}) ({c)} 7.
Qb3 Nbd7 8. Nc3 (8. O-O {transposes to the main line of chapter 5.}) 8... Nb6
9. cxd5 exd5 10. O-O Ne4 11. Bf4 c6 (11... Bf5 $11 {Daskevics - Rytshagov,
Riga 2004}) 12. Ne5 Nd6 13. Rae1 Be6 $36) 7... c6 {This move-order, instead of
7...Nbd7, which I chose as main continuation, can easily transpose, but in
this chapter we will see independent paths.} 8. Qc2 (8. Qb3 {is the main
option, where} Nbd7 {leads us to chapter 5.}) 8... Nbd7 (8... b6 {is an
important alternative, with theoretical prestige, but outside the scope of
this work.}) 9. Rd1 {This plan is the independent form of treating the
position. Instead, 9.Bf4 Ne4 transposes to our main line in the next chapters.}
Ne4 $5 {I use his move to show the differences to the main line with the
move-order 7...Nbd7.} ({But note that Magnus Carlsen, Sergey Karjakin and
Boris Gelfand, among others, play the most popular and solid continuation} 9...
b6 $5 {, where an important main line continues} 10. Bf4 Bb7 11. Nc3 dxc4 12.
Nd2 Nd5 13. Nxc4 Nxf4 14. gxf4 Qc7 15. e3 Rad8) 10. Be1 {This reorganization
was White idea.} ({My computer also likes the alternative} 10. Be3 $5 Nd6 (
10... f5 {is the alternative, setting up a Stonewall.}) 11. c5 (11. b3 b6 12.
Bf4 Bb7 13. Nbd2 f5 14. h4 {[Lysyj - Bocharov, Russia tt rapid]} Ne4 $13) (11.
Nbd2 {[Nikolajeva - Ernese, Riga 2017]} Nf5 $13) 11... Ne4 $5 ({a standard
manoeuvre to exploit the placement of he bishop on e3 is} 11... Nf5 {, but
after} 12. Bc1 {I prefer the White side, for example} b6 13. cxb6 Qxb6 14. Nc3
Ba6 {[Ju Wenjun - Henderson de La Fuente, Gibraltar 2018]} 15. Bg5 $14) 12.
Nbd2 Nxd2 13. Bxd2 b6 14. cxb6 Qxb6 15. Rdc1 (15. Rac1 c5 16. dxc5 Bxc5 17. e3
h6 $132) 15... c5 16. dxc5 Bxc5 17. e3 Ba6 $132) 10... f5 {This is the main
move, but Black has an interesting alternative in} (10... b5 $5 {Marin -
Bischoff, Capo d'Orso 2017}) 11. Nc3 {Again the most usual choice.
Alternatives are:} ({a)} 11. b4 Bf6 12. Nc3 (12. a4 {[Maslov - Klovans, URSS
1970] can be answered in the standard way with} g5 $132) 12... Nb6 13. c5 Nc4
$13 {Ernst - Van der Wiel, Vlissingen 2000}) ({b)} 11. Nfd2 b5 $5 (11... Bf6 $5
{Kamsky - Bocharov, Russia tt 2018}) 12. cxd5 cxd5 13. Nxe4 fxe4 14. Qc6 Nb6 (
14... Qb6 $5) 15. Qxb5 Nc4 $44) ({c)} 11. Nbd2 {is cited by Mihail Marin in
his work for Modern Chess on the Catalan Opening. After} a5 12. Nb3 {Black can
reply, instead of Marin's 12...a4, with} Bd6 13. Nc1 (13. Nfd2 Qf6 $13) 13...
b6 14. Nd3 (14. cxd5 cxd5 15. Nd3 Ba6 $132 {is similar}) 14... Ba6 $132) 11...
Qe8 {A standard plan in the Dutch schemes, transferring the queen to the
kingside. A possible alternative, which is still untested, is} (11... a5 $5)
12. Nd2 {Also a standard move, fighting against the advanced enemy knight.
Some alternatives are:} ({a)} 12. Rac1 Nd6 $5 (12... b6 13. cxd5 exd5 $132) 13.
cxd5 exd5 14. Ne5 Ne4 $11 {with a standard Stonewall position.}) ({b)} 12. b4
Nd6 13. c5 Ne4 $132 {followed by ...b6.}) ({c)} 12. Rab1 b6 (12... Qh5 $5 {
Lein - Chandler, Baleares 1989}) 13. cxd5 exd5 14. e3 Bb7 $13) 12... Qh5 {
Depending on the next White move, Black can follow up with ...Rf6-h6, ...Ng5
or ...g5, typical ideas in the Stonewall.} 13. Nf1 (13. Rac1 Nxd2 (13... b6 $2
14. cxd5 cxd5 15. Ncxe4 dxe4 16. Qc6 $18) (13... Nb6 14. b3 Nxd2 15. Bxd2 dxc4
16. e4 Bd7 $13) (13... Bd6 $5) 14. Bxd2 dxc4 $13) 13... Ndf6 $11 {Bielicki -
Rossetto, Havana 1964. After an interesting battle, this duel between two
classic Argentinean masters finished in a draw.} *

