1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 Be7 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O Nbd7 {
This is my recommended move-order. Please, note that it isn't better or worse
than 7...c6 from a theoretical viewpoint, but a personal preference. In this
position, Black can consider taking on c4 and later defending the pawn with ...
Nb6. Now White usually protects the pawn, either with 8.Qc2 (the main line) or
8.Qb3 (see next chapter). In this chapter, we will look at other moves,
including some new ideas.} 8. Nc3 $5 {Of course, White isn't forced to defend
c4 and can play in gambit style. As compensation for the pawn, if Black takes
on c4, he expects to build a strong centre with a future e4, where the chances
of both sides will be balanced, according to experience in similar positions.
Alternatives are:} ({a)} 8. Bf4 dxc4 (8... c6 {with the idea to transpose to
the main line, but White can also play 9.Nc3 with transposition to 8.Nc3, or}
9. Nbd2 Nh5 10. Be3 b6 $13 {Decroix - Rosenfeld, France 2014}) 9. Qc2 (9. Nbd2
c3 {[9...b5 deserves consideration, and if 10.a4 then 10...c6]} 10. bxc3 Nd5
11. c4 Nxf4 12. gxf4 c5 $13 {Meskovs - Sargsyan, internet 2019}) 9... Nd5 (9...
Nb6 {allows White to show his idea behind Bf4:} 10. Nbd2 {and the pawn is
recovered. Typical play against this idea can be seen in the line} Nfd5 11.
Nxc4 Nxf4 12. gxf4 Nxc4 13. Qxc4 c6 14. e3 {[Markus - Stojanovic, Vrnjacka
Banja (SRB-t) 2010]} Qd5 $132) (9... b5 $5 10. a4 b4 11. Nbd2 c5 $132) 10. Qxc4
b5 $5 ({Also good is the simple} 10... Nxf4 11. gxf4 c6 12. Nbd2 {[Melkumyan -
Jussupow, Quatar 2014]} Qc7 $11) 11. Qc2 (11. Qxb5 $5 Rb8 12. Qd3 Rxb2 13. Nc3
Nxf4 14. gxf4 c5 $13) 11... Bb7 12. Nc3 Nxf4 13. gxf4 c5 14. Rfd1 ({Safest is} 
14. dxc5 Nxc5 $11 {Gleizerov - Kunte, New Delhi 2012}) 14... Qc7 {Black is
doing well, for instance:} 15. e3 a6 (15... b4 $5 16. Nb5 Qb6 17. dxc5 $1 Nxc5
18. Nbd4 Rac8 19. Rac1 a5 $13) 16. d5 exd5 17. Nxd5 Bxd5 18. Rxd5 Rad8 19. Rad1
(19. a4 $5) 19... Nb6 $11 {Dominguez - Harikrishna, Tsaghkazdor 2015}) ({b)} 8.
b3 {is a solid alternative, but not dangerous for Black. Some examples are:} c6
(8... b6 $5 9. cxd5 {[Burmakin - Donchenko, Deizisau 2004]} exd5 $11) 9. Nc3 (
9. Bc3 Ne4 10. Bb2 b6 11. Nfd2 {[Ding Liren - Vidit, Tbilisi 2017]} f5 $13)
9... b6 10. Bf4 Ba6 11. Qd3 (11. Nd2 Nh5 12. Be3 Rc8 $11 {Li Chao - Wojtaszek,
China blitz 2016}) 11... Rc8 12. Rfd1 c5 13. Nb5 (13. a4 $5 dxc4 14. bxc4 {
[Bauer - Delchev, France tt 2006]} cxd4 15. Nb5 Bb7 16. Qxd4 Rc5 $13) 13...
Bxb5 14. cxb5 cxd4 {[Vyzmanavin - Illijin, Bern 1993]} 15. Rac1 Nc5 16. Qb1
Nce4 $11) ({c)} 8. cxd5 exd5 9. Nc3 c6 {is easy for the second player, because
the exchange on d5 frees the light-squared bishop and all the Black pieces can
develop in a harmonic way.} 10. Qc2 Re8 (10... Nb6 $5 {Martens - Hoeksema,
Enschede 1994}) 11. Bf4 (11. Rfe1 Bd6 $11 {Sherbakov - Kiriakov, Russia 1998})
11... Nf8 12. Rad1 (12. Rfe1 Ng6 13. Bg5 Ne4 14. Bxe7 Qxe7 $11 {Zhao Jun -
Tomashevsky, Moscow 2011}) 12... Ng6 13. Bc1 (13. Bg5 Be6 $11 {Korsunsky -
Klovans, URSS 1989}) 13... Bf8 14. Rfe1 h6 $11 {Atamer - S.Nikolov, Sofia 2009}
) ({d)} 8. Bc3 {, like the above viewed 8.Bf4, frees d2 for the knight. After}
b6 (8... Ne4 $5 9. Nbd2 Nxc3 10. bxc3 c6 11. e4 dxe4 12. Nxe4 {[Wahlund -
Kucuksari, Vaxjo 2017]} Qc7 $11) (8... dxc4 9. Nbd2 b5 10. Ne5 $44) 9. cxd5
exd5 (9... Nxd5 10. e4 Nxc3 11. Nxc3 Bb7 {[Ding Liren - Carlsen, internet 2017]
} 12. Qe2 $36 {looks easier to play for White}) 10. Nbd2 Bb7 11. Ne5 c5 12. b3
Nxe5 13. dxe5 Ne4 14. Nxe4 dxe4 15. Qc2 Qd5 16. Rad1 Qc6 17. f4 exf3 18. Bxf3
Qc8 19. Bxb7 Qxb7 20. Qf5 Qc6 $13 {Martirosyan - Donchenko, Zurich 2019. The
White initiative, which is based on the activity of his pieces, is compensated
by Black's better pawn structure. Now ...Qe6 and ...g6 are possible ideas for
the second player.}) ({e)} 8. a4 {was played in a few games, but among the
White players we find strong grandmasters as Boris Gelfand, Levon Aronian,
Ivan Cheparinov and Hrant Melkumyan... , so it definitely deserves attention.}
a5 $1 (8... dxc4 9. Na3 $14 {is one of the ideas behind the 8th Black move}) 9.
Qc2 {White tries to get a favourable version of the main line, but Black can
instead play} c6 ({It's also possible to opt for the the plan with} 9... Ne4
10. Bf4 (10. Be3 c6 11. Na3 {Yu Yangyi - Le Quang, Gibraltar 2019, can be
answered with} Bb4 $5 $132) 10... c6 {, for instance} 11. Nc3 g5 12. Bc1 f5 13.
b3 {[Roiz - Matlakov, St. Petersburg rapid 2018]} b6 $5 $132 {, with a typical
Stonewall position.}) 10. Rc1 (10. Bf4 dxc4 $5 $132) 10... Ne4 11. Be1 (11. Be3
f5 12. Nc3 Nd6 {[12...Bd6!? as in Aronian - Wei Yi, Wijk aan Zee 2019, looks
more complex]} 13. cxd5 exd5 14. Bf4 Nf6 $11) 11... f5 12. e3 Bd6 13. Nc3 Qe7
14. Rab1 g5 $13 {Voit - Ter Sahakyan, Batumi 2018}) ({f)} 8. b4 c6 (8... dxc4
9. Qc2 $44 {Bindrich - Ferreira, Batumi ol 2018}) 9. a4 Ne4 {Standard.} ({
Also interesting are} 9... Bd6 $5 {So - Karjakin, Stavanger 2018}) ({and} 9...
b6 10. cxd5 cxd5 11. Qb3 Ne4 12. Rc1 Nxd2 13. Nbxd2 Bb7 $11 {Maghsoodloo -
Karjakin, Astana 2019}) 10. Be1 {The same idea as in the previous chapter.} f5
(10... b6 $5 {with ideas like ...Ba6 or ...a5, Globus - Gonda, Budapest 2018})
11. Nc3 $5 (11. b5 {[So - Wei Yi, internet 2018]} dxc4 12. bxc6 bxc6 13. Nc3 c5
$132) (11. Qc2 $5 Bf6 12. Nbd2 Qe7 $13) 11... a5 (11... Nb6 12. c5 Nc4 $132) (
11... Bxb4 $6 12. Nxe4 fxe4 13. Bxb4 exf3 14. exf3 $16) 12. bxa5 Nd6 13. cxd5
exd5 14. Ne5 Rxa5 $132) ({g)} 8. c5 c6 (8... Ne4 $5) (8... a5 $5) 9. Nc3 b6 10.
b4 (10. cxb6 axb6 $15) 10... a5 11. a3 Ne4 12. Qc2 Nxc3 13. Bxc3 Ba6 14. Rfe1
Bb5 15. e4 axb4 16. axb4 Rxa1 (16... dxe4 17. Qxe4 Qc7 $11) 17. Rxa1 dxe4 18.
Qxe4 Nf6 19. Qc2 Nd5 $11 {Gelfand - Karjakin, Moscow rapid 2018}) ({h)} 8. Bg5
c6 ({also good is} 8... h6 9. Bxf6 Nxf6 {Ippolito - Salomon, Stockholm 2017})
9. Nbd2 (9. Nc3 b6 10. Nd2 h6 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. e3 a5 13. Rc1 Ba6 $11 {
Krasenkow - Levin, Hoogeveen 2013}) 9... b6 10. Qa4 (10. Rc1 Bb7 11. Qa4 h6 12.
cxd5 exd5 13. Bxf6 {[Kuzubov - Petrosyan, Moscow 2017]} Nxf6 $11) 10... Bb7 11.
Rfd1 h6 (11... a5 $5 {Kozul - Neverov, Bayern 2015}) 12. Bxf6 Bxf6 (12... Nxf6
$5) 13. Rac1 {(Wang Yue - Yu Yangyi, Shenzhen 2011)} Qe7 14. e4 dxe4 15. Nxe4
c5 $13) ({i)} 8. Na3 $5 {was played by Levon Aronian} c6 (8... Ne4 $5 {
Radovanovic - Ivanisevic, Kragujevac (Serbia ch) 2017}) (8... Bxa3 9. bxa3 Nb6
$13 {is another good way to challenge White's idea.}) 9. Rc1 Ne4 10. Be3 f5 11.
Rc2 {(Aronian - Karjakin, Londres 2017). Now, instead of the move 12...a5,
Black can choose among different options on the kingside, like 11...Qe8, 11...
h6 or} g5 12. Qc1 Bf6 $13) 8... dxc4 {Accepting the challenge. The main
alternative is} (8... c6 {, where} 9. Bf4 {continues offering the pawn.} (9.
Qb3 {transposes to the line 8.Qb3, see next chapter.}) (9. c5 {transposes to 8.
c5}) 9... dxc4 (9... Nh5 10. Bc1 Nhf6 11. b3 b6 {as in Gelfand - Mamedyarov,
Nakhchivan 2009 is another option, which is solid but a bit passive.}) 10. e4 {
Now we have a different scheme than in the main line, due to the different
structure. Here Black can immediately support the advanced pawn with ...b5 or,
before any action on the queenside, improve the pieces with ideas like ...Re8,
Nf8-g6.} Re8 {The second plan.} ({The alternative is} 10... b5 11. d5 Qb6 {
with a complex play, maybe more easy to play for White. For example} 12. dxc6
Nc5 13. Nd2 $36 {Zontakh - Bocharov, Russia 2010}) 11. a4 {To prevent ...b5.} (
{If} 11. Re1 {, Black can return to a better version of the first plan:} b5 12.
d5 e5 13. Nxe5 Nxe5 14. Bxe5 b4 15. Bxf6 Bxf6 16. Na4 Rb8 {[or the more
complex 16...cxd5]} 17. e5 Rxe5 18. Rxe5 Bxe5 19. dxc6 Bf5 $11) 11... b6 ({
Another idea is} 11... a5 {, planning ...b6, Ba6 as in Tregubov - Gelfand,
Odessa 2008.}) 12. d5 (12. Qe2 Ba6 13. Rfd1 Rc8 $13 {Lalith - Vitiugov, Moscow
2017}) 12... exd5 13. exd5 Bb7 14. a5 bxa5 15. d6 Bf8 16. Nd2 Nb6 (16... Nd5 $5
{Nakamura - Karjakin, Saint Louis 2018}) 17. Nde4 Nxe4 18. Nxe4 Nd5 19. Bg5 {
(Zontakh - Grigoryan, Legnica 2013)} Qc8 $132 ({or} 19... f6 $5)) 9. e4 {
The most natural try, but White also tried other moves.} (9. Qc2 Nd5 10. Rfd1 {
(Fritz - Jacobsen, Malmo 2018)} b6 $5 $13) (9. Bg5 {(N.Pedersen - Percivaldi,
Copenhagen 2018)} Nd5 $36) 9... c5 {I think that it is a good idea to attack
the centre immediately.} ({A good alternative is} 9... Rb8 $5 {as in Nihal -
Abasov, Turquia tt 2018}) 10. Bf4 {This is critical.} (10. e5 $6 Nd5 11. Qe2
Nxc3 12. Bxc3 b5 $15 {Jacobsen - Azarov, Rijeka 2010}) 10... Qb6 {More
pressure. It is also possible to settle the tension with} (10... cxd4 11. Qxd4
{(Ragozin - Levenfish, Leningrad 1936)} Qb6 $13) 11. d5 exd5 (11... Qxb2 $5)
12. e5 ({The option} 12. exd5 {leads to complex possibilities. An illustrative
line is} Qxb2 13. Rc1 Bd8 14. Nd2 Nb6 15. a4 (15. Bd6 Re8 16. Bxc5 Bf5 $11)
15... a5 16. Nde4 Bf5 17. Re1 Nxe4 18. Nxe4 Qa3 19. Nd6 Bd3 {, where White has
reasonable compensation for the pawns, but not more than that.}) 12... d4 13.
exf6 Nxf6 14. Na4 Qa6 $13 {Yuffa - Steinberg, Jerusalem 2018. The pawn mass on
the queenside gives Black interesting compensation for the piece.} *

[Event "5.Bd2 - 8.Qb3"]
