1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 Be7 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O Nbd7 8.
Qc2 {We are entering the main line of this system. With his last move, White
defends the c4-pawn and fights for the control of the e4 square. If he were
allowed to make several moves in a row, those were Bf4, Nbd2 and e4. In our
scheme, Black anticipates that idea by occupying e4, usually assuming a
Stonewall formation.} Ne4 ({The main alternative is} 8... c6 9. Bf4 b6 {
(8... Ne4 transposes to the text), a safe and solid variation that is outside
the scope of this work. I recommend it as a useful alternative if our main
line needs to make a pit stop for some reason.}) 9. Nc3 {This is the main
alternative to the more popular and logical 9.Bf4, which will be considered in
the next chapters. White also has several other options:} ({a)} 9. Rd1 {
is a very popular alternative. After} c6 10. Nc3 (10. Be1 f5 {[%emt 0:00:03]
transposes to a line analysed in chapter 3.}) (10. Bf4 g5 11. Be3 f5 12. Nc3 {
[Giri - Carlsen, internet 2017]} f4 13. gxf4 gxf4 14. Bc1 Ng5 $13) (10. Be3 Nd6
11. b3 b6 12. Bf4 Bb7 13. Nbd2 {[Lysyj - Bocharov, Russia rapid 2018]} c5 $11)
(10. a3 a5 11. Bc3 {[Halkias - Blohberger, Skopje 2019]} Nxc3 12. Qxc3 b6 $11)
10... Nxd2 11. Nxd2 Rb8 12. e4 (12. a4 a5 13. e3 {[Bjelobrk - Song, Canberra
2019]} Bb4 $5 14. f4 Qf6 $132) 12... dxe4 13. Ndxe4 f5 14. Nd2 e5 $11 {Lei
Tingjie - Tari, Wijk aan Zee B 2017. This is similar to our main line - only
Rfd1 and ...Rb8 were included.}) ({b)} 9. Bc1 c6 10. b3 a5 11. Nbd2 f5 12. a4
Bb4 $11 {Pedersen - Azarov, Philadelphia 2018}) ({c)} 9. Be3 Nd6 10. b3 (10.
Nbd2 Nf5 11. Qd3 c6 12. Rac1 Nxe3 13. Qxe3 {[Karavade - Fridman, internet 2018]
} Re8 $11) 10... dxc4 11. bxc4 Nf5 $132) ({d)} 9. Rc1 c6 10. Be1 f5 (10... a5
$5) 11. e3 (11. b4 Bf6 $13 {Rashkovsky - Balashov, Elista 1995}) 11... g5 (
11... a5 $5) 12. Nc3 g4 (12... Bd6 $5) 13. Nd2 {(Karczmarczyk - Antognini,
Switzerland tt 2018)} Ng5 (13... Ndf6 $5) (13... Rf6 $5) 14. f4 gxf3 15. Nxf3
Nxf3+ 16. Bxf3 Nf6 $11) ({e)} 9. cxd5 exd5 10. Bf4 c6 11. Nc3 Ndf6 $11 {
Parol - Baskin, Warsaw 2018}) ({f)} 9. a3 a5 10. Nc3 Nxd2 11. Nxd2 c6 12. Rfd1
Rb8 13. e3 b5 14. cxb5 cxb5 15. Bf1 b4 16. Nb5 {(Shoboev - Bocharov, Khanty
Mansiysk 2018)} Ba6 $11) 9... Nxd2 10. Nxd2 {Black won the pair of bishops and
White some influence in the centre, with the e4-move at his disposal.} c6 11.
e4 {The immediate central push is the most common plan, but White didn't
achieve great results with it. The alternatives are:} ({a)} 11. Rfd1 Rb8 {
transposes to the line 9.Rd1} ({Black can also try} 11... f5 {as in Svane - So,
Gibraltar 2019, but I'm rather sceptical about it.})) ({b)} 11. Rad1 {is
recommended by Marin in his work for Modern Chess. Now I like} Rb8 $5 ({
instead of} 11... f5 12. e3 Bd6 13. a3 Qe7 14. f4 b6 15. Nf3 Bb7 16. Ne5 Kh8
17. b4 $14 {Marin - Lupulescu, Alba Iulia rapid 2017}) ({or} 11... Bf6 12. e3
b5 13. cxb5 cxb5 14. Nxb5 $14 {Koustav - Gaifullin, Moscow 2019}) 12. f4 (12.
e3 b5 $5 $13) 12... b5 (12... Nf6 13. Rfe1 c5 $132) 13. c5 b4 14. Na4 f5 $13 {
with ideas like ...Nf6-e4, ...Ba6-b5 and ... g5. The position offers chances
for both sides.}) ({c)} 11. e3 Rb8 12. a3 a5 13. Rfc1 dxc4 14. Nxc4 b5 15. Ne5
(15. Nd2 Qb6 $11) 15... Nxe5 16. dxe5 Qc7 17. Ne4 (17. Qe4 c5 $36 {Batchuluun
- Oparin, Vladivostok 2016}) 17... Qxe5 18. Qxc6 b4 $13) ({d)} 11. cxd5 exd5
12. a3 {(Tilicheev - Golinsky, Moscou 2011)} Nf6 13. Rfe1 Qb6 14. e3 a5 15.
Rac1 g6 $5 $13) 11... dxe4 $5 {This is my recommendation, but the other
capture is also good and most popular in practice:} (11... dxc4 12. Nxc4 Nb6
13. Nxb6 (13. Ne2 Nxc4 14. Qxc4 {[Bachmann - Akobian, internet 2019]} e5 15.
dxe5 Qa5 16. f4 Be6 17. Qc3 Bb4 18. Qc2 Qc5+ 19. Qxc5 Bxc5+ 20. Kh1 Rad8 $44)
13... Qxb6 14. Rad1 e5 $5 15. d5 (15. dxe5 Bg4 16. Ne2 Qb5 17. f3 Be6 $44)
15... Bg4 16. Rd3 {(Bullen - Oschner, Batumi ol 2018)} Rfd8 $11) 12. Ndxe4 (12.
Ncxe4 f5 13. Nc3 e5 {transposes.}) 12... f5 13. Nd2 e5 $1 {Black has easy
equality, for instance:} 14. dxe5 {Alternatives are:} ({a)} 14. Nb3 a5 $11 {
Sermier - Petrov, Switzerland 2018}) ({b)} 14. d5 c5 (14... e4 15. Rad1 Qe8 16.
Rfe1 Qh5 $15 {Dimarucut - Bellahcene, Dubai 2019}) 15. Nb5 (15. Rae1 Bd6 16.
Nb5 Bb8 17. Nc3 e4 $13) 15... Nf6 16. Rae1 a6 17. Nc3 Bd6 $15 {Mulyar -
Chandra, Wisconsin 2017}) ({c)} 14. Ne2 exd4 15. Nxd4 Ne5 $11) 14... Nxe5 15.
Rfe1 ({Against} 15. Rad1 {(Molenda - Sadzikowski, Suwalki 2017) Black can play
the energetic} f4 $5 {, where a possible continuation is} 16. Nf3 Nxf3+ 17.
Bxf3 Qc7 $36) 15... Qc7 16. Nf3 {This is a logical idea, fighting against the
centralized black pieces. Alternatives are:} ({a)} 16. Nb3 f4 $36 {Lewtak -
Sadzikowski, Katowice rapid 2018}) ({b)} 16. Ne2 $5 {is a computer favourite,
but after} Bc5 $11 {Black has easy play.}) ({c)} 16. Re2 {was White's choice
in Predojevic - Nisipeanu, Baku ol 2016, where Black missed the chance to
acquire a strong initiative with} f4 ({though the game move} 16... Bf6 {
wasn't so bad either.}) 17. Rae1 Ng6 $15 {, with the idea to play .. .Bf5 next.
}) 16... Nxf3+ (16... Ng4 $5) (16... Bf6 $5) 17. Bxf3 Bf6 $11 {Markoja -
Oleksiyenko, Slovenia tt 2017. The bishop pair offers Black a good long-term
perspective.} *

