[Black "Catalan 4...Bb4+"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "E11"]
[Annotator "IM Luis Rodi"]
[PlyCount "28"]
[EventDate "2018.12.08"]
[EventCountry "RUS"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 Be7 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O Nbd7 8.
Qc2 Ne4 9. Bf4 c6 {This is the basic position from our development scheme. We
can arrive here using various move-orders, although each of them presents a
series of independent sublines.} 10. Nbd2 {With this way of development, which
is very natural but not especially dangerous, we open this section. One of the
problems that I find in this move is that it is passive and also restricting
the Bf4. The most popular moves, 10.Nc3 and 10.Nfd2, are considered in the
next chapters. Other alternatives are:} ({a)} 10. Ne5 {First played in Benko -
Korchnoi, Stockholm izt 1962. Black can react with} g5 $1 11. Bc1 (11. Be3 Nd6
$11 {Walter - Banus, Germany tt 2017, and Black can follow up with ...Nf5.})
11... f5 12. Nxd7 Bxd7 13. Nd2 Bf6 $11 {Izsak - Pinter, Hungary 2001.}) ({b)} 
10. Ne1 {is another idea of Benko's, intending f3. After} g5 (10... Bf6 $5 {
deserves consideration, with the idea} 11. Bxe4 dxe4 12. Qxe4 c5 $44) 11. Bc1
f5 12. b3 {(Buslaev - Nei, Palanga 1961)} (12. a4 Bf6 13. e3 Bg7 $13) 12... b6
(12... b5 $5 13. f3 Nd6 14. c5 Nf7 $11) 13. Nc3 (13. cxd5 cxd5 14. Qc6 Ndf6 $1
$13) 13... Bb7 14. Bb2 Nd6 $13 {The position offers chances to both sides.}) ({
c)} 10. h4 $5 {A proof of respect for the intrinsic strength of the ...g5 move,
first played in 2005. OK, White prevents the black idea, but his move is not
very active, while Black still has several resources.} h6 {Insisting on the
idea ...g5. Alternatives are:} (10... Ndf6 {This has the seal of approval of
the World Champion.} 11. Nbd2 (11. a4 $5) ({and} 11. Nc3 {are perhaps more
critical tries.}) 11... Nxd2 12. Nxd2 (12. Bxd2 b6 13. Ne5 Bb7 $132) 12... Nh5
(12... dxc4 $5) 13. Be3 f5 14. Bf3 {(Meier - Carlsen, Baden Baden 2018)} f4 $5
15. Bxh5 fxe3 16. fxe3 Qd6 17. Rxf8+ Bxf8 18. Kg2 e5 19. cxd5 cxd5 20. e4 exd4
$13) (10... f5 {is another natural move. I don't know if the move h4 is so
terrible against the Classical Stonewall, but seems to me that Black position
is very much playable, to say the least.}) 11. Nc3 g5 $5 (11... f5 12. Nxe4
fxe4 13. Ne5 {was played in Xiong - Le Quang, Saint Louis 2019. Now 13...Bxh4
doesn't work due to 14.Ng6, and the game continuation} Nxe5 (13... Bxh4 14. Ng6
Rf6 15. Nxh4 Rxf4 16. gxf4 Qxh4 17. e3 $16) 14. Bxe5 Bf6 15. f3 $14 {is
slightly better for White.}) 12. Be3 Nd6 13. b3 (13. hxg5 hxg5 14. c5 Nf5 15.
Bc1 g4 16. Nh2 Nxd4 17. Qd1 e5 18. Nxg4 f5 19. Nxe5 Nxe5 20. Qxd4 Bf6 $44)
13... f5 (13... Nf5 $6 14. Bc1 g4 15. Nh2 Nxd4 $2 16. Qd2 $18) 14. a4 Rf7 15.
hxg5 hxg5 16. Rfd1 Bf6 $13 {with chances for both sides.}) ({d)} 10. Rd1 g5 11.
Bc1 f5 12. Nc3 (12. Ne1 {[Flumbort - Zakarias, Hungary tt 2019]} Bf6 $132)
12... b6 {This move from Gajewski seems here the most exact.} ({other
possibility is} 12... Bf6 13. Ne1 Qe7 {Ostojic - Nestorovic, Paracin 2017}) 13.
b3 (13. cxd5 cxd5 14. Ne1 Bb7 15. Nxe4 $2 dxe4 $17 {Arngrimsson - Gajewski,
Iceland tt 2018}) (13. Ne1 Bb7 14. Nxe4 dxe4 15. f3 c5 16. d5 exf3 17. exf3
exd5 18. f4 Bf6 $13) 13... Bb7 14. Bb2 Qe8 $13 {with chances for both sides.})
10... g5 $1 {It's time to do some explaining about this apparently risky move,
which is standard in this variation and in this type of positions, winning
space on the kingside while gaining time on the enemy dark-squared bishop.
Usually Black continues with ...f5, solidifying the e4-square, or, when the
threatened bishop retreats to e3, with the manoeuvre ...Nd6 (with a new gain
of tempo due to the threat against c4), ...Nf5. Obviously, this advance also
weakens the Black king, but the White pieces can't exploit this in the near
future, because the key squares in this area are controlled by Black.} 11. Be3
Nd6 (11... f5 {is also popular, but it shows inferior results to the more
flexible text. A recent sample with this alternative is} 12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. Ne5
Nxe5 14. dxe5 Qc7 15. Qc3 c5 16. Rad1 Bd7 17. Qc1 h6 18. h4 Bc6 19. hxg5 Qxe5
20. gxh6 Kh7 $11 {Kucuksari - Jacobsen, Gothenburg 2019}) 12. cxd5 {This is
the only move tested in practice, but isn't critical. Generally the exchange
on d5 frees the Black light-squared bishop and gives Black easy equality.
Instead, White can try:} ({a)} 12. c5 {is also not good, due to the logical
reply} Nf5 $15) ({b)} 12. Rfd1 f5 (12... Nf5 13. Nf1 a5 $13) 13. c5 Nf7 $13) ({
c)} 12. h4 $5 gxh4 13. gxh4 Kh8 $13) 12... exd5 13. Nb3 {isn't any better:} (
13. Ne5 Re8 (13... Nf5 $5 14. Nxc6 Nxe3 15. Nxe7+ Qxe7 16. fxe3 Qxe3+ 17. Kh1
Nb6 $11 {Ivlev - Kobo, St. Petersburg 2018}) (13... Nb6 $5 14. f4 $6 Bf5 $15 {
Bloomer - Robson, internet 2019}) 14. f4 Nf8 15. Rae1 Nf5 $15) 13... a5 $5 {
This move hasn't been tried in practice yet.} (13... Nb6 {was Ray Robson
choice.} 14. Rae1 $5 {This is better than} (14. Rad1 {In this concrete line,
d1 is an unfortunate placement for the queen's rook.} Nbc4 15. Qc1 (15. Bc1 Bf5
$17) (15. Nc5 Nxe3 16. fxe3 Qe8 $17) 15... f6 16. Nc5 Nf5 $17 {Ramos - Robson,
Batumi ol 2018}) 14... Re8 (14... Nbc4 15. Bc1 Bf5 16. Qd1 Re8 {transposes.})
15. Bc1 $5 (15. Qc1 f6 16. Bd2 Ne4 17. Ba5 Bd6 $36) 15... Bf5 16. Qd1 Nbc4 17.
Nc5 Ne4 18. Nxb7 Qb6 19. Nc5 Nxb2 20. Qc2 Nc4 $11) 14. Nc5 Nc4 $15 {I prefer
Black in this complex position, because his pieces look better coordinated and
he already has the initiative.} *

