1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 Be7 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O Nbd7 8.
Qc2 Ne4 9. Bf4 c6 10. Nfd2 {This move has the endorsement of grandmaster Boris
Avrukh, recommended in his excellent books on 1.d4. But the next move isn't
mentioned in his work:} g5 $5 {Ambitious and good.} ({Of course,} 10... f5 {
is also possible, but White scored great results here.} 11. Nxe4 fxe4 12. Nd2
Bf6 13. Bd6 Rf7 14. e3 $14 {is Avrukh's line, based on the game Kaidanov -
Benjamin, Long Beach 1993. In this line, White can also try 12.Nc3, as in
Niemann - Kretchetov, Philadelphia 2019.}) ({Avrukh's main line runs} 10...
Nxd2 11. Nxd2 g5 12. Be3 f5 13. f3 $5 Rf7 14. Bf2 Nf8 15. e4 Ng6 {(Lautier -
Bareev, Dortmund 1995)} 16. exf5 exf5 17. cxd5 cxd5 18. f4 gxf4 19. Qb3 $44 {
, a position which the Israeli grandmaster considers better for White.}) 11.
Be3 {The main move. Alternatives are:} ({a)} 11. Nxe4 gxf4 12. Ned2 Bd6 (12...
b5 $5 13. cxd5 cxd5 14. Nf3 {14.gxf4 seems more critical. Black, when Black
has reasonable compensation for the pawn.} b4 15. Nbd2 Ba6 16. Rfe1 Bb5 17.
gxf4 Rc8 18. Qb3 Qc7 19. Ne5 Qc2 $44 {Carbone - Rodi, Colonia del Sacramento
2018}) (12... fxg3 13. hxg3 f5 {is the usual continuation, leading to a
typical Stonewall position where White can claim a slight advantage, for
instance:} 14. Nc3 Nf6 15. e3 Ne4 {[Hilverda - Buhmann, Austria tt 2018]} 16.
Nf3 $14) 13. Nc3 Qg5 14. Nf3 Qg6 (14... Qg7 $5) (14... Qh5 15. Qd3 a5 $13) 15.
Rac1 dxc4 16. Ne4 Bc7 17. Rfd1 a5 $13 {, with chances for both sides.}) ({b)} 
11. f3 $2 gxf4 12. fxe4 fxg3 13. hxg3 dxe4 14. Nxe4 f5 15. Ned2 Nf6 $19 {
Einarsson - Dziuba, Iceland tt 2017.}) ({c)} 11. cxd5 exd5 12. Be3 Nd6 13. Nc3
Nb6 14. f3 $6 {(Li Xueyi - Martin Duque, Lisbon 2019)} f5 $17 {While White has
better options on his 14th move, Black, as mentioned, doesn't have any
problems after the exchange on d5.}) 11... Nd6 {This is a standard manoeuvre
against schemes with White's dark-squared bishop on e3.} ({One more time the
natural} 11... f5 {is an option, as in Steinbacher - Brenninkmeijer, Groningen
1994, but I think that the text move is better.}) 12. Nc3 {While this is not
the most usual, it looks like the most active and interesting white choice.
The alternatives are:} ({a)} 12. f3 {is the most common in practice, but Black
has easy equality after} f5 13. Bf2 f4 (13... Nf6 $5 {Raja - Gutierrez
Olivares, Gibraltar 2019}) 14. Nc3 (14. e4 fxe3 15. Bxe3 Nf5 16. Bf2 Bf6 $11 {
Cherniaev - Tarjan, Canada 2017 and later games.}) 14... Kh8 $5 (14... Rf7 $5)
15. e4 fxe3 16. Bxe3 dxc4 17. Nde4 Nf5 18. Bf2 Nb6 19. Rad1 Nd5 20. Qe2 b5 $11
{White has compensation for the pawn, but certainly no more than that.}) ({
b) As in similar positions, the exchange on d5 isn't especially ambitious, but
here it is even inferior:} 12. cxd5 exd5 13. Nc3 Nb6 $5 ({instead of} 13... f5
14. Nf3 Nb6 $11 {Vantika - Batchuluun, Abu Dhabi 2017}) 14. Rae1 Nf5 15. Qd3
Bf6 $15) 12... Nf5 $5 {An idea among others of equivalent value:} ({a)} 12...
b5 $5 {This is a remarkable decision, forcing White to define the queenside.}
13. cxb5 (13. c5 Nf5 $11) 13... cxb5 14. Nb3 b4 15. Na4 Nb6 16. Nbc5 (16. Nac5
a5 $11) 16... Nf5 $11) ({b)} 12... f5 13. c5 (13. f4 g4 $11 {or 13...Nf6!?})
13... Nf7 (13... Ne8 $5 {followed by ...Nef6 is other idea.}) 14. f3 (14. b4 $5
Nf6 $13) 14... e5 $13 {Godart - Glud, Batumi ol 2018}) ({c)} 12... a5 $5 13.
Rae1 (13. cxd5 exd5 14. f4 h6 $13) 13... dxc4 14. Qc1 b5 $5 15. Bxc6 Rb8 $13)
13. cxd5 (13. Qd3 {prevents the doubled pawns, but after} Nb6 {Black is fine,
and again the exchange on e3 is a strategical threat.} 14. Rad1 (14. b3 e5 $17)
14... e5 (14... Nxe3 15. fxe3 (15. Qxe3 dxc4 16. f4 Nd5 17. Qf3 b5 $15) 15...
f5 16. g4 $5 $13) (14... h5 $5) 15. c5 Nxe3 16. Qxe3 Nd7 $15) 13... Nxe3 14.
fxe3 exd5 15. Rad1 (15. e4 $5 dxe4 16. Ndxe4 (16. Qxe4 Nb6 $11) 16... f5 17.
Nf2 Nb6 $11) 15... Nb6 16. e4 Be6 17. exd5 ({Another try is} 17. Qd3 dxe4 $5 (
17... Qd7 18. Nb3 $14 {Cerrato - Schiendorfer, corr 2010}) 18. Bxe4 (18. Ndxe4
a5 $13) 18... f5 19. Bxf5 Bxf5 20. Rxf5 Rxf5 21. Qxf5 Qxd4+ 22. Kg2 Qf6 $11 {
As in many lines of this variation, we have reached a dynamically balanced
position. White is more active, but Black has the better pawn structure.})
17... Nxd5 {This recapture is better than} (17... cxd5 18. e4 Rc8 {, where
White position is preferable, Daeschler - Ma Qun, Vandoeuvre 2019.}) 18. Nxd5
cxd5 {is roughly equal, for example} 19. e4 Rc8 20. Qd3 dxe4 21. Bxe4 (21. Qxe4
Qd7 $11) 21... f5 22. Bxb7 (22. Bxf5 Bxf5 23. Rxf5 Rxf5 24. Qxf5 Qxd4+ 25. Kh1
Rc6 $11) 22... Rb8 23. Bc6 (23. Bg2 Rxb2 24. d5 Bc8 25. Nc4 Bc5+ 26. Kh1 Ba6
27. Rxf5 Rxg2 28. Kxg2 Rxf5 29. Qxf5 Bxc4 30. Qe6+ Kg7 31. Qe5+ Kg8 32. Qe6+
$11) 23... Rxb2 $11 *

