1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 Be7 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O Nbd7 8.
Qc2 Ne4 9. Bf4 c6 10. Nc3 {The main line. Now Mikhail Botvinnik's move caught
my attention, played in two highly instructive games: Petrosian - Botvinnik,
Moscow 1963, in their World Championship match and Eljanov - Carlsen, Wijk aan
Zee 2016.} g5 $1 {In the Dutch Defence, Black's expansion on the kingside is a
standard method. In this concrete line, the move-order is different but the
idea the same: To build a Dutch Stonewall position with aggressive space gain.}
11. Be3 {The alternative 11.Bc1 is analysed in the next chapter.} ({A third
possibility,} 11. Bd2 {, looks less logical to me. After} g4 (11... f5 {
Pham - Vo, Vietnam 2013}) 12. Ne5 (12. Ne1 Nxd2 13. Qxd2 dxc4 14. Nc2 f5 $15)
12... Nxd2 13. Qxd2 (13. Nxd7 Bxd7 14. Qxd2 f5 15. c5 Qc7 16. Rae1 h5 $15)
13... f5 {Black is more than fine, for instance:} 14. f4 gxf3 15. Nxf3 Nb6 16.
c5 Nc4 17. Qc1 e5 18. b3 exd4 19. bxc4 dxc3 20. Nd4 Bxc5 21. Qxc3 Qf6 22. Rad1
b6 23. cxd5 Ba6 24. Rf2 Rad8 25. e3 cxd5 26. Bf1 Bc8 $15) 11... Nd6 {This is
my preference.} (11... f5 {is the alternative, as in Schneider - Blohberger,
Austria 2019.}) 12. b3 {The most common. Alternatives are:} ({a) The harmless} 
12. cxd5 {is unfairly popular. After} exd5 {Black's pieces improve their scope
while White has nothing in return.} 13. Rad1 (13. Bd2 Nb6 14. b3 Bf5 15. Qc1 f6
16. Ne1 Bg6 17. Nc2 Re8 $15 {Shvidler - Zubov, Israel tt 2019}) (13. Qc1 h6 14.
h4 f6 15. Na4 Nb6 16. Nc5 Nbc4 17. b3 Nxe3 18. Qxe3 {[Kezin - Vakhlamov,
Moscow 2017]} Qe8 $17) (13. Rae1 $5 f5 $36) 13... Nb6 14. Qc1 (14. b3 Bf5 15.
Qc1 f6 16. Nd2 Bg6 17. f3 f5 $15 {Moayed - Cordova, Batumi ol 2018}) (14. Ne1
a5 15. a4 Bf6 16. f3 Bg7 $15) 14... f6 15. b3 a5 16. Ne1 Nf5 17. Nc2 Nxe3 18.
Qxe3 {(Skatchkov - Matlakov, Russia tt 2018)} a4 $15) ({b)} 12. c5 Nf5 13. Bh3
(13. g4 $2 {is poor compared to the similar position from the game Eljanov -
Carlsen that we will see later:} Nxe3 14. fxe3 h5 15. gxh5 g4 16. Nd2 Bg5 17.
Qd3 f5 $17 {Zeynalov - Oleksiyenko, Cesme 2018}) (13. Nd1 g4 14. Ne5 Nxe3 15.
Nxe3 Nxe5 16. dxe5 h5 $17) 13... Nxe3 14. fxe3 Kg7 $17) 12... Nf5 {Magnus
Carlsen's choice. From the point of view of decision making in the opening,
Black avoided obtaining a typical rather solid but passive Catalan position in
order to create imbalances with risks for both sides. I am not so much
convinced by the alternative} (12... b5 $5 {, where the only practical example,
although it finished with a Black victory, lead to a good position for the
first player:} 13. Qc1 f6 14. h4 g4 15. Nh2 bxc4 16. Nxg4 Kh8 17. Bf4 Nb6 18.
e4 $14 {Cuenca Jimenez - Anton Guijarro, Gibraltar 2019.}) ({Taking the pawn
is clearly weaker:} 12... dxc4 $6 {Among several good options, White has} 13.
Bc1 $5 $14 {followed by the advance e4.}) 13. Bd2 {This remarkable pawn
sacrifice was recommended by Alexey Kuzmin as the best white continuation, The
alternatives are:} ({a)} 13. g4 $5 {This was Eljanov's reaction in his game
against Carlsen. A determined action! It allows the structural damage of
doubled pawns but gives him the opportunity to play actively on the kingside
as well.} Nxe3 14. fxe3 b5 $5 {Carlsen has a special feeling for the
initiative, which he shows here once again. The World Champion understands
that to fight for the initiative in this position, he must not shy away from
material concessions. Black wants to gain squares for his undeveloped pieces
while at the same time distracting White's knight away from the kingside.} ({
The decision of the world champion is very human; my computer on the other
hand suggests the alternative} 14... h5 {The idea is to take on g4 and follow
up with ...f5. If} 15. h3 {, then} Kg7 {with the possibility to transfer the
rook to the h-file.}) 15. e4 $5 {As before, Eljanov doubles the bet again,
ignoring the queenside provocation in favour of further central actions.
Objectively this isn't the best possibility, although the game gains in
complexity.} ({Instead,} 15. cxb5 cxb5 16. Nxb5 Qb6 {offers compensation
similar to positions from the Benko (Volga) Gambit, with Black using the open
files on the queenside. A possible continuation is:} 17. Nc3 Ba6 18. e4 Rac8
19. Qd2 h6 $44) 15... b4 $5 {Very ambitious.} ({A more simple alternative is} 
15... bxc4 16. bxc4 dxc4 {Black is slightly better here, although White has
some compensation.}) 16. exd5 $6 {A brave piece sacrifice in exchange for some
pawns and activity, further raising the degree of complexity. Unfortunately,
this decision is a mistake. Instead, several retreats of the queen's knight
should be considered:} (16. Nd1 {has the idea of a transfer to e3, increasing
the chances of an initiative on the kingside, but it's too slow:} dxc4 17. bxc4
c5 $1 $15) (16. Na4 {is a plan diametrically opposed to the previous one, with
the focus on the queenside and more control over c5, although the black
position is easy after} dxc4 17. Qxc4 Nb6 18. Nxb6 Qxb6 $36 {Even so, this may
be the best option for White.}) 16... bxc3 17. dxc6 Nb8 $1 $17 {Eljanov -
Carlsen, Wijk aan Zee 2016. The World Champion won the battle of the opening
and later the game.}) ({b)} 13. cxd5 Nxe3 14. fxe3 exd5 15. e4 $5 (15. Bh3 {
[Bosiocic - Bindrich, Austria tt 2017]} Nb6 $15) 15... dxe4 (15... Nb6 {
is another good reply here}) 16. Qxe4 f5 17. Qd3 (17. Qe6+ Kh8 18. Qe3 Nb6 $11)
17... Bf6 (17... Nb6 $5) 18. Rad1 Nb6 {with chances for both sides.}) ({
c) White can also play} 13. Qd2 {, when} g4 (13... h6 $5) 14. Ne1 dxc4 (14...
Nxe3 15. Qxe3 Nb6 16. Qd3 f5 $36 {is another idea}) 15. bxc4 Nb6 {is good for
the second player, as the white pieces remain passive.}) 13... g4 14. Ne1 Nxd4
(14... dxc4 {isn't very satisfactory for Black.} 15. e3 $14) 15. Qd1 Bf6 {
This is the only move tested in practice, but Black have some interesting
alternatives involving an exchange sacrifice:} ({a)} 15... Ne5 $5 {deserves
serious consideration. For the exchange Black wins a pawn and the bishop pair,
which gives him reasonable compensation:} 16. Bh6 Nf5 17. Bxf8 Qxf8 18. Nd3 (
18. e3 h5 $44) 18... Nxd3 19. Qxd3 d4 20. Na4 e5 21. Rae1 h5 22. Be4 Ng7 $5 $44
) ({b)} 15... dxc4 $5 {is another way to give away the exchange, but more
difficult for Black:} 16. Bh6 Ne5 17. Bxf8 Kxf8 18. bxc4 Nf5 19. Qc1 $5 (19.
Qxd8+ Bxd8 20. c5 Be7 $44) (19. Qb3 Qd4 20. Rd1 Qxc4 $13) 19... Qd4 (19... Nxc4
20. Nd3 Qa5 21. Ne4 $14) 20. Nd3 Nxd3 21. exd3 Bf6 22. Qa3+ Be7 23. Qb3 $14) ({
c) Finally,} 15... h5 $5 16. Bh6 Nf5 17. Bxf8 Qxf8 {is also possible, but after
} 18. cxd5 exd5 19. e4 $14 {White's position is better.}) 16. e3 Nf3+ 17. Nxf3
gxf3 18. Qxf3 ({The other recapture,} 18. Bxf3 {leads to balanced play after}
Nc5 19. Rc1 Nd3 20. Rb1 Bg7 $11) 18... Bg7 {This is better than the
alternatives} ({a)} 18... dxc4 19. Qg4+ Bg7 20. Qxc4 $14) ({b)} 18... Ne5 19.
Qe2 dxc4 20. f4 (20. Ne4 $5 {seems to be stronger}) 20... Nd3 21. bxc4 $16 {
Jojua - Paichadze, Georgia tt 2017.}) 19. Qe2 {This was the choice of
Alexander Grischuk in a recent game.} (19. Rfd1 Qe7 20. Rac1 (20. cxd5 {
preserves the structure, but frees the enemy light-squared bishop.} exd5 (20...
Ne5 21. Qe2 exd5 $11) 21. h3 Ne5 22. Qe2 Bf5 $11) 20... dxc4 21. bxc4 e5 $11 {
With roughly equal chances.}) 19... b6 20. Rac1 $5 (20. e4 dxc4 (20... Ba6 21.
exd5 cxd5 22. Rac1 Rc8 23. Rfd1 $14 {Grischuk - Nakamura, Paris (blitz) 2019})
21. Rad1 Qe7 (21... cxb3 22. axb3 $44) 22. bxc4 Ba6 $13) 20... Ba6 {Chances
are roughly equal. Black's pieces show good activity, his structure is solid
and the king, although somewhat bare, isn't in any concrete danger. A possible
continuation is:} 21. Nd1 f5 22. Bb4 c5 23. Bc3 Qe7 24. Bxg7 Qxg7 25. Nb2 Nf6
26. Rfd1 Rad8 $13 *

