1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 Be7 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O Nbd7 8.
Qc2 Ne4 9. Bf4 c6 10. Nc3 g5 11. Bc1 {The main move, which was already played
in the first game with this variation in the match for the World Championship
title between Mikhail Botvinnik and Tigran Petrosian in 1963.} f5 {After this
advance, Black gets an active position in Stonewall style. At first glance,
the difference from the original Dutch opening seems to be in Black's favour,
who is a few tempi ahead. This gives him a strong grip on e4 and the
positional basis for a quick expansion on the kingside. Meanwhile, White also
has his standard ideas: His control of the e5 square, the presence of a bad
bishop in Black's camp, and he can hope to exploit the weaknesses created by
the advance of the black kingside pawns.} 12. b3 {This was Petrosian's choice,
and it continues to be the most popular in practice. Of course, White also
experimented with other ideas:} ({a)} 12. Rd1 {is the second move in
popularity.} b6 {Practical experience shows that it's important in this type
of position to quickly develop the light-squared bishop.} ({A common move in
this kind of position is} 12... Bf6 {, played in Tratatovici - Gorodetzky,
Israel tt 2018, but maybe here it isn't so accurate.}) 13. Ne1 $5 (13. cxd5 {
isn't critical} cxd5 14. Ne1 Bb7 $11 {Arngrimsson - Gajewski, Iceland tt 2018})
13... Bb7 14. Nxe4 dxe4 15. f3 (15. c5 Qc7 $13) 15... c5 (15... exf3 $5 16.
Nxf3 $14) 16. d5 exd5 17. cxd5 Bf6 $5 {Black gives up a pawn, but the position
remains close to balanced.} 18. fxe4 fxe4 19. Qxe4 (19. Bxe4 Qe7 $44) 19... Qe8
20. Qe6+ Qxe6 21. dxe6 Bxg2 22. Kxg2 (22. exd7 Bh3 $17) (22. Nxg2 Ne5 $44)
22... Ne5 23. Nf3 Nxf3 24. exf3 Rfe8 25. Re1 Rad8 $44) ({b)} 12. Ne5 {is
premature; Black equalizes easily after} Nxe5 13. dxe5 Qc7 (13... Qa5 $5) 14.
Nxe4 (14. f4 $6 {[Maiwald - Ruf, Germany tt 1992]} Qb6+ 15. e3 gxf4 16. Na4 Qa5
17. exf4 Rd8 $15) 14... dxe4 15. Qc3 b6 $11) ({c)} 12. Rb1 Bf6 ({As in similar
positions,} 12... b6 {is a reasonable option.}) 13. Rd1 Qe7 14. Nd2 $5 ({
In practice White only played} 14. b4 {, but Black has several good
continuations here: 14...a6 (Lalic - Spraggett, Spain 1996), 14...Nb6 
(Grabuzova - Schleining,Germany tt 1994) and the still unplayed} b5 $5 {
In all of the cases the second player fights for the advantage.}) 14... Qg7 (
14... Nxd2 15. Rxd2 dxc4 16. e4 Qg7 17. e5 Be7 18. b3 $44) 15. e3 h5 $13) ({d)
} 12. e3 Bd6 (12... g4 13. Ne1 h5 $13) 13. b3 Qe7 14. Bb2 g4 15. Ne1 {(Postny
- Mindlin, Israel ch 2018)} b6 16. a4 a5 $132) ({e)} 12. Nd2 {(Gunina - Di
Benedetto, Hersonissos 2017)} Qe8 $5 (12... Nxd2 13. Bxd2 dxc4 {is an option})
13. Ndxe4 (13. f3 Nxc3 14. Qxc3 f4 $15) 13... dxe4 14. Bd2 Rb8 15. Rae1 Bf6 $13
) ({f)} 12. Ne1 Bf6 ({or} 12... Nd6 13. cxd5 exd5 14. Nd3 Nf7 15. Bd2 Bf6 16.
e3 Bg7 $11) 13. e3 Qe7 14. Nd3 (14. a4 b6 15. b4 $5 Bb7 $13) 14... b6 15. b3
Bb7 16. Bb2 {(Sviridov - Banusz, Minsk 2017)} c5 $13) ({g)} 12. a4 a5 13. b3
Rf7 14. Ba3 {is Roiz - Matlakov, St. Petersburg rapid 2018). Now easiest is}
Bxa3 15. Rxa3 b6 $11) ({h)} 12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. Nd2 {(Gledura - Duda, Gibraltar
2016)} Qc7 $13) ({i)} 12. cxd5 exd5 13. Rd1 h6 14. Ne5 Nxe5 15. dxe5 Qe8 $15 {
Morejko - Pantzar, Lisbon 2019}) ({j)} 12. Be3 {One of the preferences of my
computer, now that Black doesn't have the manoeuvre ... Nd6-f5.} Nd6 13. c5 Nf7
$132) 12... b6 $1 {This move, with the idea ...Bb7, was recommended by Alexey
Kuzmin in the New in Chess Yearbook 118, and since then it has been played
with good results for Black.} ({The first game with the line 10...g5 continued
instead with} 12... Bf6 {, which is still the most common move in practice.}
13. Bb2 Bg7 14. Rad1 $14 {Petrosian - Botvinnik, Moscow (9) 1963}) 13. Bb2 {
The usual continuation. Also deserving of attention is the alternative} (13.
Nd2 {, when} Nxc3 (13... Nef6 $5 {lead to a draw by repetition in Perez Lopez
- Rook, corr 2018 after 14.Nf3 Ne4, but White can try} 14. Bb2 Ba6 15. Nf3 $14)
(13... Nxd2 $5 {is a good alternative to the text:} 14. Qxd2 (14. Bxd2 Ba6 $13)
14... Bb7 15. Qe3 Kf7 $13) 14. Qxc3 Nf6 15. Nf3 $5 (15. Bb2 Bd7 {Perhaps the
immediate 15...g4 is more exact.} 16. Rac1 g4 17. f3 h5 $11 {Mareco - Akobian,
Saint Louis 2017}) 15... Ne4 16. Qe3 Bb7 (16... f4 $6 17. Qd3 $14 {, and Black
loses control of the important e4-square.}) 17. Bb2 Bf6 (17... Rc8 18. Ne5 Bf6
19. f3 Nd6 20. cxd5 exd5 21. Rac1 $14) 18. Ne5 Qe7 19. f3 Nd6 20. cxd5 exd5 21.
Qd2 Rac8 $11 {, with roughly balanced play.}) 13... Bb7 14. Rad1 {A logical
and popular try. Alternatives are:} ({a)} 14. Ne1 Nd6 15. Na4 (15. cxd5 exd5
16. Nd3 Rc8 $132) (15. Nd3 Rc8 {[15... dxc4!?]} 16. Rac1 {[Velilla - Jonsson,
corr 2016]} Qe8 $132) 15... Rc8 (15... Qe8 $5) 16. Nd3 Ba6 17. c5 Nf7 $13 {
Gibas - Glatzel, corr 2015} ({or} 17... Ne4 $5 $13)) ({b)} 14. a4 a5 (14... g4
15. Ne1 a5 $132) 15. Ne1 Nd6 16. Nd3 Rc8 17. cxd5 cxd5 18. Rfc1 Ba6 19. Qd1 Nf6
$132 {Perez Lopez - Rook, corr 2018}) 14... Qe8 15. Ne5 $5 {This move looks
like the critical try.} ({a) Harmless is} 15. Nxe4 dxe4 16. Ne1 Nf6 $11 {
Tripp - Brindza, corr 2017}) ({b)} 15. Nd2 {also doesn't cause trouble to the
second player:} Nd6 (15... Nxc3 16. Qxc3 g4 {is another possibility.}) 16. Ba3
Rc8 17. Rfe1 Nf7 (17... Qf7 $5) 18. Qb2 Nf6 19. Bxe7 Qxe7 20. b4 Rfd8 21. e3 g4
22. cxd5 cxd5 $11 {So - Nakamura, Saint Louis (USA ch) 2017}) 15... Nxe5 16.
dxe5 Nxc3 17. Qxc3 {We are following Le Quang - Nakamura, Saint Louis rapid
2017. Now I prefer:} Rd8 18. cxd5 cxd5 19. Qd3 Bc5 $11 *

