1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. g3 {White delays the advance c4. This move-order is
used to avoid the lines with a quick...dxc4 and, of course, also our main
recommendation with the check on b4. While this isn't a problem for players
with the Closed Catalan in their repertoire, if for some reason the reader
prefers other types of positions he also has independent options as mentioned
in this chapter.} e6 {Giving a new opportunity for c4 that White rarely makes
use of.} (3... Bf5 {and 3. ..Bg4 are other interesting and very solid tries
that can be investigated by the reader.}) 4. Bg2 b5 $5 {Making sure that the
white player will regret his decision of delaying c4. Now it's too late! This
move was first played in the master arena by Romanishin in 1973, and
recommended by Boris Avrukh in his book "Beating the 1.d4 sidelines" in 2012.}
5. O-O {Castling is very natural, and the most usual move in this position.
The main alternatives, by order of popularity, are:} ({a)} 5. a4 b4 6. c4 (6.
O-O Bb7 {transposes to the main line}) (6. a5 $5 {can be answered with Avrukh's
} Ba6 $13) 6... bxc3 7. Nxc3 (7. bxc3 Nbd7 8. O-O Ba6 9. Na3 ({or} 9. Nbd2 c5
10. Re1 Be7 11. e4 Nxe4 12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. Rxe4 O-O $11 {Szymanski - Jedynak,
Krakow 2005 and other games.}) 9... c6 (9... Ne4 $5 {is a recent try:} 10. c4
c6 11. cxd5 cxd5 12. Nb5 {[Korpa- Vogel, Le Casella 2018]} Be7 $132) 10. c4 {
(Barbero - Bednarski, Naestved 1988)} Be7 11. cxd5 exd5 $5 (11... Nxd5 {
is Avrukh's recommendation.}) 12. Qc2 O-O {Black doesn't need to defend the
pawn c6 yet. The following sequence leads to roughly equal play:} 13. Ne5 Nxe5
14. dxe5 Ng4 15. Qxc6 Bxe2 16. Re1 Nxe5 17. Qxd5 Qxd5 18. Bxd5 Rad8 19. Rxe2
Rxd5 20. Bb2 Ng6 $11) 7... Nbd7 8. O-O (8. Bf4 Bd6 $5 $132) 8... Ba6 9. Bf4 (9.
Re1 Bb4 $11 {Lodhi - Miroshnichenko, Abu Dhabi 2006}) (9. Qc2 Bd6 10. Nb5 O-O
11. Bf4 Qb8 {[Filippov - Vaulin, Russia 2001]} 12. Nxd6 cxd6 13. Rfb1 Rc8 $13)
